President Obama convened his National Security Council to discuss progress in the campaign against ISIL and efforts to help the Syrian people. The meeting focused on the ongoing aggressive campaign against ISIL, which involves military, intelligence, law enforcement, and diplomatic efforts. The President emphasized the importance of preventing attacks on the United States and countering terrorist threats from ISIL and al-Qa'ida in Syria. The President was also updated on Coalition efforts to pressure ISIL across Syria and Iraq. The meeting also addressed discussions with allies and partners about the violence in western Syria and the Asad regime's actions against its own people. Despite suspending bilateral channels with Russia, the President directed his team to continue multilateral discussions with key nations to encourage a diplomatic resolution to the civil war and a reduction in violence.